WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:06.190 --> 00:00:09.250
&gt;&gt; Amy Puryear: It's a pleasure
for me to introduce Tonya Bolden.

00:00:09.250 --> 00:00:15.120
She is an award winning author
of over 20 children's books,

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:19.700
and she's written about the
emancipation proclamation.

00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:24.160
She's written about Martin Luther
King, and she has won a number

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:30.150
of awards and today, she's
going to talk about the museum

00:00:30.150 --> 00:00:35.030
that opened today of African
American history and culture.

00:00:35.030 --> 00:00:38.510
Please welcome Tonya Bolden.

00:00:38.510 --> 00:00:41.520
[ Applause ]

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:42.820
&gt;&gt; Tonya Bolden: Hi.

00:00:42.820 --> 00:00:44.120
Good afternoon.

00:00:44.120 --> 00:00:45.420
Can you hear me?

00:00:45.420 --> 00:00:46.720
Okay. Good.

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:48.020
Good afternoon again.

00:00:48.020 --> 00:00:49.320
Thanks for being here.

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:53.490
Thanks for coming with love
and joy and faith and hope.

00:00:53.490 --> 00:00:55.110
I really think we're
in a crossroads,

00:00:55.110 --> 00:00:56.910
and I should have asked
one of my hosts

00:00:56.910 --> 00:01:00.830
to take my pocketbook,
but that's okay.

00:01:00.830 --> 00:01:03.210
And earlier today -- oh, it's cool.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:04.620
It's fine, baby.

00:01:04.620 --> 00:01:07.010
Earlier today, I had
some time in the hotel,

00:01:07.010 --> 00:01:09.140
and I was watching, I guess, NBC.

00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:11.700
And I'm watching, and
I'm saying, "Don't cry.

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:13.000
Don't cry."

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:14.300
John Lewis comes.

00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:15.600
I'm like, "Don't cry.

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:16.900
Don't cry."

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:18.200
And I said, "You're going
to be all puffy eyed."

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:19.500
And I was like, "Oh, well.

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:20.800
Hide behind my glasses."

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:22.480
But let me start with this.

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:28.580
A museum is a treasure trove of
things, things lost then found,

00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:34.100
things perennially prized, things
-- objects once deemed worthless.

00:01:34.100 --> 00:01:38.620
Whatever a museum collects,
paintings, pottery

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:41.740 position:56%
or play things, its aim is the same.

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:47.770
To safeguard remnants of history
and culture that inspire, enlighten

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:51.260
and kindle the curiosity of the
children and adults who come

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:55.650
through its doors,
generation after generation.

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:58.940
Smithsonian's National Museum
of African American History

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:03.290
and Culture is a treasure trove of
paintings, photographs, posters,

00:02:03.290 --> 00:02:07.600 position:56%
[inaudible], pottery, documents,
dolls, diaries, books, balls, bells,

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:09.990
benches, medals, medallions
and more.

00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:13.010
Objects that deepen
our understanding

00:02:13.010 --> 00:02:15.190
of the black experience in America

00:02:15.190 --> 00:02:19.110
and so strengthen our
grasp of American history.

00:02:19.110 --> 00:02:23.060
This is the story of
how that magnificent

00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:26.660
and monumental museum got built.

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:30.030
So it was February, 2014.

00:02:30.030 --> 00:02:34.120
I received an email through
the account that's attached

00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:37.810
to my website, which means somebody
I don't know who doesn't know me

00:02:37.810 --> 00:02:40.060
because friends have
the other email.

00:02:40.060 --> 00:02:42.310
So I get this email, and the
subject line is something

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:44.440
like possible project.

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:46.480
And this woman introduces herself.

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:48.760
Her name is Sheila Keen,
and she's with Viking.

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:51.700
I do not know her, but she
knows my work, and she says,

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:55.020
"I'd like to talk to you
because -- about an idea."

00:02:55.020 --> 00:02:57.810
She basically said that I
think it's right up your alley.

00:02:57.810 --> 00:02:59.110
So we talk.

00:02:59.110 --> 00:03:03.930
And the project was this
book, How to Build a Museum.

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:08.050
The museum that took 13 years to
build but 100 years to come about.

00:03:08.050 --> 00:03:10.270
Now, I had all kind of problems
-- because, right, we're always --

00:03:10.270 --> 00:03:11.840
you have something in production.

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:13.550
You have something
on the first draft.

00:03:13.550 --> 00:03:14.850
You have something
else, this [inaudible].

00:03:14.850 --> 00:03:16.150
And you always have all this stuff.

00:03:16.150 --> 00:03:19.830
Plus it was February, which is
like equal employment opportunity

00:03:19.830 --> 00:03:21.720
for black writers and illustrators.

00:03:21.720 --> 00:03:25.270
So I'm thinking I'm feeling
overwhelmed, but I just said

00:03:25.270 --> 00:03:27.520
to self so you won't sleep some.

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:33.860 position:56%
I could not not do this book because
the museum represents everything

00:03:33.860 --> 00:03:38.730
that I'm about, like large --
like a thousand times over.

00:03:38.730 --> 00:03:42.980
So I said I'll get a little less
sleep, but I have to do this book

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:49.630
because history is my passion and
because [inaudible] the last museum

00:03:49.630 --> 00:03:54.030 position:56%
in the mall is the first Smithsonian
Museum built from scratch.

00:03:54.030 --> 00:03:59.370
And so I think in many ways
[inaudible] is sort of reflective

00:03:59.370 --> 00:04:03.500
of black lives upon these shores.

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:05.320
It was a long time coming.

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:07.190
A hundred years to come about.

00:04:07.190 --> 00:04:11.400
People were campaigning for
this back in 1915, 1916.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:13.990
Meanwhile, other museums
and galleries go up

00:04:13.990 --> 00:04:17.480
and people continue to
believe in the dream.

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:21.350
The dream really started as
a monument to black veterans

00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:24.760
in the American Revolution
and all the other wars onward.

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:27.490
And they couldn't -- they didn't
have any friends in court,

00:04:27.490 --> 00:04:30.470
but they kept campaigning
and the dream got bigger.

00:04:30.470 --> 00:04:36.280
So this was a book that I had to
do because it is about, as I said,

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:39.710
everything that I'm about
[inaudible] I think sums it up.

00:04:39.710 --> 00:04:41.130
Now you know the [inaudible]
symbols.

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:43.910
I think it's usually presented
as a bird with a neck,

00:04:43.910 --> 00:04:46.490
a very limber bird, but the neck
is sort of turned back [inaudible].

00:04:46.490 --> 00:04:50.810
And some people --
what does it mean?

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:55.160
Some people say go
back and pick it up.

00:04:55.160 --> 00:04:59.030
Some people simply say remember.

00:04:59.030 --> 00:05:00.600
I like to use it as remember.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:01.900
I know that's something

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:04.240
that [inaudible] is all
about is remembering.

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:09.000
But there's a minister, a Baptist
minister, in Brooklyn, New York.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:13.310
He translates [inaudible] as
the way out is back through.

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:15.930
What does he mean by that?

00:05:15.930 --> 00:05:21.180
The way out is back through.

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:24.510
You all shy?

00:05:24.510 --> 00:05:27.090
[ Inaudible ]

00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:28.390
Okay, yeah.

00:05:28.390 --> 00:05:31.480
And I think, for example,
the way out is back through.

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:34.790
It's saying you have
-- history is vital.

00:05:34.790 --> 00:05:38.700
It's saying as MLK said
we are made by history,

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:44.110 position:56%
and Baldwin said history is
literally present in all that we do.

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:46.900
So if you take someone
[inaudible] remember,

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:49.590 position:56%
you take someone of African descent.

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:54.950
The way out through lingering shame
and fear and doubt and despair is

00:05:54.950 --> 00:05:58.510
to go back and pick up that history
and find out whence you come.

00:05:58.510 --> 00:06:01.070
I think the wonderful thing
about the museum that makes it

00:06:01.070 --> 00:06:04.620 position:56%
so fantastic is it really, really
shows that people of African descent

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:07.350 position:56%
in this country are not bit players.

00:06:07.350 --> 00:06:11.180
And I'm constantly always
telling people that if we came

00:06:11.180 --> 00:06:16.260
from a nothing people, people
like me wouldn't exist.

00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:21.040 position:56%
[Inaudible], I think too as you know
the museum basically is saying what

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:22.610
I always try to say in my books is

00:06:22.610 --> 00:06:24.340
that black history is
everyone's history.

00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:27.030
I also think that all the
histories are everyone's history.

00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:28.330
I always say that the building

00:06:28.330 --> 00:06:30.390
of the transcontinental
railroad is my history.

00:06:30.390 --> 00:06:32.330
The trail of tears is my history

00:06:32.330 --> 00:06:34.240
because we are all
made by the history.

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:38.160
And so you may have someone
who's not of African descent

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:41.140
who may not know intimately
any black people

00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:43.680
and so maybe they hold
stereotypes about them.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:48.400 position:56%
And maybe they think when they see
them from afair up in the helicopter

00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:50.580
that they all look like bad dudes.

00:06:50.580 --> 00:06:54.930
And maybe, though, if you go to
the museum and you read more books,

00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:58.700
maybe you'll see wow, black people
are as different and complex.

00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:01.300
Yeah, there's some bad dudes among
us and some bad girls among us

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:06.040 position:56%
and all that, but there's also
Jacob Lawrence and Thurgood Marshall

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:10.020
and geniuses and [inaudible]
and all of that.

00:07:10.020 --> 00:07:11.950
That's why we need the
history because it's

00:07:11.950 --> 00:07:17.470
about educating ourselves, and I
think we're at a crossroads now,

00:07:17.470 --> 00:07:22.070 position:56%
and the only hope -- I think we
have to decide whether we want to go

00:07:22.070 --> 00:07:29.440
into insanity and stupidity or if
we really want to take another stab

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:32.930
at getting this country to
live up to its own ideals,

00:07:32.930 --> 00:07:36.770
to catch up its own ideals.

00:07:36.770 --> 00:07:40.080
So again, everyone
needs the history.

00:07:40.080 --> 00:07:43.950
Needs to understood, too, as
the museum will show that yes,

00:07:43.950 --> 00:07:45.450
there's slavery and Jim Crow.

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:46.750
There was pain.

00:07:46.750 --> 00:07:48.050
There was tears.

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:49.350
There was sorry.

00:07:49.350 --> 00:07:50.650
But it's also about the jubilees.

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:51.950
It's about celebrating.

00:07:51.950 --> 00:07:53.250
It's about praise.

00:07:53.250 --> 00:07:54.550
It's about uplift.

00:07:54.550 --> 00:07:56.760
The whole design of the
museum is praise and uplift

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:59.760
so that you say yeah, you had
the slaughter and the beatings

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:03.970
and the brandings on the cheeks and
people getting their ears cut off

00:08:03.970 --> 00:08:07.250
because they tried to run
away or getting a finger --

00:08:07.250 --> 00:08:09.670
[inaudible] of their index finger
chopped off because they tried

00:08:09.670 --> 00:08:10.970
to learn to read and write.

00:08:10.970 --> 00:08:15.660
But you also had people escape
like Josiah Henson carrying his kid

00:08:15.660 --> 00:08:19.090
on his back until his
back got raw and bled.

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:22.500 position:56%
You have going on down the line,
you have people like Michael Shiner.

00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:25.580
I did a book about him, Michael
Shiner, about his journal.

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:29.860
In D.C., he was an incredible man
with agency here in Washington,

00:08:29.860 --> 00:08:32.780
D.C. Then later on down the
line, you have the people

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:37.670
who fought the 54th glory
corps and on down on down.

00:08:37.670 --> 00:08:39.670
You have Charles Dorsey,
Tommy Dorsey.

00:08:39.670 --> 00:08:41.540
You have Thurgood Marshall.

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:43.460
You have Jacob [inaudible].

00:08:43.460 --> 00:08:47.250
You have -- and we go on and on
and on to the point where you have

00:08:47.250 --> 00:08:51.310
in the White House
Barack Hussein Obama.

00:08:51.310 --> 00:08:54.410
And one of the things I did
last night as I was privileged

00:08:54.410 --> 00:08:59.160 position:56%
and honored to attend the Library of
Congress gala for the book festival.

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:02.470
And there, it was the first
-- I belive I'm correct --

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:08.850
public event presided over by
the 14th Librarian of Congress,

00:09:08.850 --> 00:09:12.010
Carla Hayden, a black woman.

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:13.600
[ Applause ]

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:18.350
And that tells us that
so much is possible,

00:09:18.350 --> 00:09:21.320
and I think it was Obama
referenced this in his speech.

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:23.270
Somebody did, but I'm
always telling kids is

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:25.800 position:56%
that Jim Crow was not that long ago.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:29.320
My parents lived in a
Jim Crow South Carolina.

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:31.870
Civil War was not that long ago.

00:09:31.870 --> 00:09:36.290
So yes, we have enormous promise --
problems, but if you'd look at it,

00:09:36.290 --> 00:09:39.970
you can say, "Wow, we have
made some giant strides.

00:09:39.970 --> 00:09:41.800
We have made some progress."

00:09:41.800 --> 00:09:46.300
And we can't let people
turn us around now.

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:49.780
Now -- not at this moment
because what we're talking

00:09:49.780 --> 00:09:53.610
about is not just white
people and black people.

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:55.620
We're talking about all the people

00:09:55.620 --> 00:09:59.420
because this nation is
becoming something different.

00:09:59.420 --> 00:10:03.150 position:56%
I did a school visit in the Bronx,
and I didn't know what the kids were

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:07.400 position:56%
because there were some that were
part Latino, part black, part white,

00:10:07.400 --> 00:10:10.240
part Japanese, and I
looked at all these colors

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:11.540
and all these beautiful kids.

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:13.270
And I said, "This is beautiful."

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:16.290
And they all -- I can imagine when
they have international night,

00:10:16.290 --> 00:10:18.090
that school must be really jumping.

00:10:18.090 --> 00:10:20.660
But I looked at it and said,
"This is a good thing."

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:23.290
Because all the multiculturalism
is a good thing

00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:25.250
because then we all
learn from each other.

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:27.870
And I can't help multiculturally
because when I grew up --

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:32.400
I grew up in the 60's in a
place called East Harlem,

00:10:32.400 --> 00:10:34.120
also called Spanish Harlem.

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:38.570
And at the time, it was --
it used to be Little Italy.

00:10:38.570 --> 00:10:44.430
So I had Latinos, mostly Puerto
Ricans around me, Italians,

00:10:44.430 --> 00:10:45.730
and they would have their festivals

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:47.150
with the saints marching
in the street.

00:10:47.150 --> 00:10:49.040
You have people from the Caribbean.

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:51.460
I remember one guy from
Trinidad would do steel drumming

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:52.760
in the park at night.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:54.940
You had Africans, and
you had people like me,

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:56.980
my parents been in this country.

00:10:56.980 --> 00:11:00.530
And to me, it was like life was
a festival and life was rich

00:11:00.530 --> 00:11:03.370
and my friend, Rosa,
introduced me to [inaudible].

00:11:03.370 --> 00:11:05.800
And I thought that's a good thing.

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:07.100
I would never want
to make [inaudible]

00:11:07.100 --> 00:11:09.950
because that's also a lot
of work or from Italians.

00:11:09.950 --> 00:11:11.850
I would see them marching
around with the saints,

00:11:11.850 --> 00:11:13.750
and I [inaudible] a
little something like that.

00:11:13.750 --> 00:11:18.110
And I think growing up --
because I wrote in a poem once --

00:11:18.110 --> 00:11:22.930
when I grew up, being multicultural
wasn't an agenda or work.

00:11:22.930 --> 00:11:25.010
It was the every day way of life.

00:11:25.010 --> 00:11:28.770
And again, my father worked in
the garment center so I knew

00:11:28.770 --> 00:11:31.600
about the [inaudible] and
egg creams and all that.

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:33.470
And to me, it was like wow.

00:11:33.470 --> 00:11:35.170
Spice, spice.

00:11:35.170 --> 00:11:38.780
So, that's why I'm sort of
devoted to multiculturalism

00:11:38.780 --> 00:11:42.860
in a very gut kind of way and
because being in New York,

00:11:42.860 --> 00:11:45.440
I don't know anything else.

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:46.990
I see [inaudible] on the trains.

00:11:46.990 --> 00:11:48.290
I see Muslims on the train.

00:11:48.290 --> 00:11:49.590
I see Asian people.

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:52.140
I see Japanese, Chinese,
and I just know

00:11:52.140 --> 00:11:56.500
that I think I'm a richer
person for being in a city

00:11:56.500 --> 00:11:58.210
where I can meet the world.

00:11:58.210 --> 00:12:02.180
Where's my science -- okay.

