they're presented as getting through

00:25:10.610 --> 00:25:14.410
but not retaining their humanity.

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:18.030
And saying -- we're
not usually presented

00:25:18.030 --> 00:25:20.250
as loving, loving family members.

00:25:20.250 --> 00:25:23.590
We know about all the separation,
but no one talks about the love.

00:25:23.590 --> 00:25:28.060
So I think that always
is precious to me.

00:25:28.060 --> 00:25:33.810 position:56%
I think what made me stop and think
with the Jim Crow card that they had

00:25:33.810 --> 00:25:37.370
to lower into the museum
before it was even built --

00:25:37.370 --> 00:25:39.650
because you remember the Jim Crow
-- the Jim Crow [inaudible] --

00:25:39.650 --> 00:25:42.730
but then I thought about it, and
when I realized people can walk

00:25:42.730 --> 00:25:44.800
through it, they're going
to experience that --

00:25:44.800 --> 00:25:47.520
the front 2/3 for white
people has bigger everything

00:25:47.520 --> 00:25:49.790
and nicer everything,
and the back --

00:25:49.790 --> 00:25:52.610
and when I realized people
would walk through it,

00:25:52.610 --> 00:25:56.890
I in myself envisioned people
on the Jim Crow [inaudible].

00:25:56.890 --> 00:26:01.250
I imagined you're black and
you're going to a funeral.

00:26:01.250 --> 00:26:04.250
On top of that grief,
you got to ride Jim Crow.

00:26:04.250 --> 00:26:07.990
And then I thought, too,
when I could visualize it,

00:26:07.990 --> 00:26:09.920
very often we talk about Jim Crow.

00:26:09.920 --> 00:26:13.780
We talk about what it did to
and against black people, right?

00:26:13.780 --> 00:26:17.020
But it also victimized white
people because I thought wow,

00:26:17.020 --> 00:26:18.940
you had this car and
you have someone

00:26:18.940 --> 00:26:21.670
who could have been a professor
at Tuskegee or whatever

00:26:21.670 --> 00:26:24.980 position:56%
and the white people in the front
aren't getting to know these people,

00:26:24.980 --> 00:26:27.190
and these people love like
them and laugh like them,

00:26:27.190 --> 00:26:29.980
and maybe they could have had
something to offer each other.

00:26:29.980 --> 00:26:32.080
So it makes you say oh my God.

00:26:32.080 --> 00:26:34.540
This was really [inaudible]
and bad for everyone.

00:26:34.540 --> 00:26:41.800
So I think because I had
to think about the objects

00:26:41.800 --> 00:26:45.180
and because I was looking at
them from the files they sent,

00:26:45.180 --> 00:26:50.480
I was able to sort of sense
memory and so being there myself.

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:51.900
So I hope that helps.

00:26:51.900 --> 00:26:53.200
&gt;&gt; Beautiful.

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:54.500
Thank you.

00:26:54.500 --> 00:26:55.800
&gt;&gt; Tonya Bolden: Two minutes left?

00:26:55.800 --> 00:26:57.100
Yes?

00:26:57.100 --> 00:26:59.760
&gt;&gt; The monument looks
beautiful from outside.

00:26:59.760 --> 00:27:02.900
I haven't visited yet inside.

00:27:02.900 --> 00:27:08.740
But my question is is it front
of the Washington Monument,

00:27:08.740 --> 00:27:13.840
and it's difficult to see that
beautiful Washington Monument.

00:27:13.840 --> 00:27:17.080
The location -- what
can you tell about that?

00:27:17.080 --> 00:27:19.320
&gt;&gt; Tonya Bolden: I don't think
it blocks it because I know

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:21.760
in fact I think its
angle had to be shifted,

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:24.940
and that's the reason I think it's
one of the most below ground --

00:27:24.940 --> 00:27:27.680
it has more stories underground
than any other thing --

00:27:27.680 --> 00:27:30.230
was precisely not to
mess up sight lines.

00:27:30.230 --> 00:27:32.870
So like I said, I haven't
physically been there,

00:27:32.870 --> 00:27:36.290
but I don't think it blocks because
I think they were very careful

00:27:36.290 --> 00:27:39.350
about sight lines of
everything on the mall.

00:27:40.980 --> 00:27:42.280
Thank you.

00:27:42.280 --> 00:27:44.580
Yes?

00:27:45.590 --> 00:27:50.990
&gt;&gt; What was your favorite
book and why?

00:27:50.990 --> 00:27:52.880
&gt;&gt; Tonya Bolden: In the
world or written by me?

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:54.180
&gt;&gt; Written by you.

00:27:54.180 --> 00:27:55.480
&gt;&gt; Tonya Bolden: Oh.

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:56.890
Right now, it is How
to Build a Museum.

00:27:56.890 --> 00:28:01.180
This is my absolutely favorite
book in the whole wide world.

00:28:01.180 --> 00:28:06.710
But when January comes around and
the a book called Pathfinders,

00:28:06.710 --> 00:28:10.900
the stories of 16 extraordinary
black souls comes out,

00:28:10.900 --> 00:28:13.940
that might be my favorite
and then in May

00:28:13.940 --> 00:28:20.380
when Crossing Ebeneezer Creek comes
out, my novel about Sherman's march

00:28:20.380 --> 00:28:22.870 position:56%
to the sea, that may be my favorite.

00:28:22.870 --> 00:28:24.330
But I have to say this right now.

00:28:24.330 --> 00:28:28.750
You guys are my favorite
audience, and we are out of time.

